      "createdAt": "2026-03-25T21:53:20.072179+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, it's great that you're paying attention to how your body is responding to training — that kind of self-awareness is genuinely one of the things that separates good runners from great ones. And the fact that you're thinking proactively about fueling at this stage of your marathon build shows real commitment to getting this right.\n\nI want to make sure I give you the most useful response here, so let me be upfront about where my expertise starts and stops.\n\n---\n\n**On the lightheadedness — this one I want to flag clearly.**\n\nLightheadedness after runs can have several causes, and some of them do warrant a conversation with a doctor — including, yes, iron status, but also hydration, blood pressure responses, fueling timing, and other things I'm simply not qualified to assess. I'd genuinely encourage you to see your GP before we assume it's iron and self-supplement. Iron supplementation when you don't need it isn't benign, and getting a simple blood panel will give you a real answer rather than a guess. That's the most useful thing you can do with that symptom right now.\n\n---\n\n**On the meal plan and keto — I have to be honest with you here too.**\n\nDesigning specific meal plans or dietary protocols is outside my lane as a running coach, and I'd be doing you a disservice if I tried. For something as specific as a ketogenic approach during a high-volume marathon build, a **registered sports dietitian** is genuinely the right person — someone who can look at your whole picture, not just the running.\n\nWhat I *can* share is some general context on the fat adaptation question, if that's useful — but I want to check first: **what have you heard about keto and marathon running, and what's drawing you toward it?** I'd rather start from what you already know than talk at you.\n\n---\n\n**On the energy struggles during long runs — this is squarely in my world.**\n\nLooking at your recent training, you've been doing some solid work: a 26 km long run, marathon pace sessions, tempo, intervals — all in the same week. That's a meaningful load. Before we look at diet, I'm curious about something more immediate:\n\n**What does your fueling look like *during* your long runs?** Are you taking on carbohydrates while you're out there, and if so, when and how much?\n\nThe reason I ask: at your current long run distances and paces, carbohydrate availability mid-run is often the biggest lever for energy — more immediately impactful than dietary strategy at home. It's worth understanding what's happening in the run itself before we look further upstream.\n\nWhat's your current mid-run routine?"
        }
      ],
